Title (title;en): Study of the engine of a De Havilland DH-89 Dragon Rapide in the Swissair commercial pilot course in Dübendorf
Description (description;en): Pilot training: meteo and radio. On January 4, 1943, Swissair started a commercial pilot course with the following participants, all of whom later successfully completed the course: Hellmuth Erni (1917-1999), Kurt Herzog (1918-), Ferdi Länzlinger (1916-2003), Walo Ris (1915-1970), Ruedi Schärer (1913-?), Ferdi Schmid (1916-2003), Guy Steiner (1917-1993).
Is part of (eth_is_part_of;en): Traffic pilot course, pilot training, meteo, radio, 1943. Reportage with 72 pictures (selection digitized, no additional motifs available).

Title (title;en): Douglas DC-3-227A HB-IRO and Douglas DC-3-216 HB-IRA on the ground in Dübendorf
Description (description;en): In the background: buildings of the military airfield. The loaded HB-IRO is ready for takeoff
Copyright notice (eth_copyright_notice;e: ETH Library Zurich, Image Archive / LBS_SR01-03079
Comments (eth_comments;en): Werner Liechti: Swissair operated a special flight Dübendorf via Brindisi to Athens on 25.04.1946. The air waybill and the cargo manifest (image LBS_SR01-03090) confirm that the aircraft was the DC-3 HB-IRO and that it was primarily a diplomatic shipment from the Swiss Vaccine Institute. Transported were 25 boxes of vaccine against foot and mouth disease, plus 2 boxes of cameras and a package of mail. Source for the flight date: Swiss Airmail Handbook (Swiss Aerophilatelists Association SAV). 2nd dating for all images:25.04.1946. : The Douglas DC-3-227A HB-IRO (front) and the Douglas DC-3-216 HB-IRA on the ground at Dübendorf, in the background the buildings of the military airfield. Description: The loaded HB-IRO is ready for takeoff.

Title (title;en): Douglas C-47 B-5-DK DC-3 Freighter, HB-IRD on the ground in Basel-Mulhouse
Description (description;en): Radio reporter Werner Hausmann from the Basel radio studio (l. with microphone) interviews a pilot at the Basel-Mulhouse airfield about the night mail flight with a DC-3 to Amsterdam. The airport "Basel-Mulhouse" was opened on May 8, 1946 in Blotzheim (F). In just six weeks, a temporary runway 1200 meters long and 40 meters wide was built of perforated steel plate. France provided the site, Switzerland the hangar and the barracks
Is part of (eth_is_part_of;en): Night mail route Basel - Amsterdam with C-47B HB-IRD (Swissair freighter), 1946-1948. Report with 37 pictures (selection digitized, no additional motifs available)
Copyright notice (eth_copyright_notice;e: ETH Library Zurich, Image Archive / LBS_SR01-03350

The helicopter was from 22.9. - 30.9.1948 on a demo tour in Switzerland among other things also in Dübendorf as your photos prove. The swiss. Fliegertruppen showed great interest in this new aircraft; However, other helicopters were procured later. On 23.9.1948, on the initiative of the then PTT, the first Swiss helicopter mail took place with this machine.

Title (title;en): First landing of the Boeing 747 B (Jumbo) of TWA in Zurich-Kloten
Description (description;en): The first B747 arrived in Zurich as part of a TWA training program, the main purpose of which was to familiarize technical ground staff at the airports of London, Paris, Frankfurt, Zurich, Geneva, Rome, Milan, Athens, Madrid and Lisbon with the new aircraft
Is part of (eth_is_part_of;en): B 747 of TWA, details, 1970. reportage with 62 pictures (selection digitized, no additional motifs available)
Copyright notice (eth_copyright_notice;e: ETH Library Zurich, Image Archive / LBS_SR03-09765-02-07
Comments (eth_comments;en): Werner Liechti: On the morning of February 8, 1970, a new era began for Kloten when TWA's Boeing 747 N93103 touched down on the blind runway. The mighty aircraft came to Zurich as part of a TWA training program, the primary purpose of which was to familiarize technical ground personnel at the airports of London, Paris, Frankfurt, Zurich, Geneva, Rome, Milan, Athens, Madrid and Lisbon with the new aircraft. TWA became the first carrier to begin operations on domestic U.S. routes with the B-747 on Feb. 25. Regular service over the North Atlantic also began on March 18. Zurich, however, is not served by the B-747s of TWA and Swissair until [1971]. Source: Ulrich Haller in Cockpit March 1970.
